{"type":"message","id":"86cac3ea","parentId":"5e521148","timestamp":"2026-04-01T12:51:18.791Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Vou criar o novo doc canónico de implementação do S1 no repo, separado do checkpoint do workspace.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0785557c08065f410169cd14c405088190b64acfb02ca78c77\",\"phase\":\"commentary\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_MgyCtVfP2dHbhFnr5fwuBOVj|fc_0785557c08065f410169cd14c800c08190ac6f516f9e6a710c","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-ChildItem -File 'docs\\implementation\\s1' | Select-Object Name,FullName","workdir":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory","yieldMs":10000,"timeout":30},"partialJson":"{\"command\":\"Get-ChildItem -File 'docs\\\\implementation\\\\s1' | Select-Object Name,FullName\",\"workdir\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\",\"yieldMs\":10000,\"timeout\":30}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_EQhoFQr0O0WmmQxL9xnsphvw|fc_0785557c08065f410169cd14c8022c8190b685df944c372945","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\contracts\\s1\\s1_supervisor_contract.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\docs\\\\contracts\\\\s1\\\\s1_supervisor_contract.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_2TiLoxH2wzB6RQGPSTNOyFfD|fc_0785557c08065f410169cd14c80238819083598c8eb400892e","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\runtime\\s1\\README.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\runtime\\\\s1\\\\README.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_xZ2kap9YrVjqmzQgiTF6Owa0|fc_0785557c08065f410169cd14c802448190a0b0fae9fc295339","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\runtime\\s1\\supervisor_runtime.py","offset":1,"limit":120},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\runtime\\\\s1\\\\supervisor_runtime.py\",\"offset\":1,\"limit\":120}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":144205,"output":240,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":144445,"cost":{"input":0.3605125,"output":0.0036,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.3641125}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775047867727,"responseId":"resp_0785557c08065f410169cd14be19f88190a27694f48c5ccbbb"}}
{"type":"message","id":"de852ce3","parentId":"86cac3ea","timestamp":"2026-04-01T12:51:20.295Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_MgyCtVfP2dHbhFnr5fwuBOVj|fc_0785557c08065f410169cd14c800c08190ac6f516f9e6a710c","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"(no output)"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":434,"aggregated":"","cwd":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775047880100}}
{"type":"message","id":"b6a27b6f","parentId":"de852ce3","timestamp":"2026-04-01T12:51:20.479Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_EQhoFQr0O0WmmQxL9xnsphvw|fc_0785557c08065f410169cd14c8022c8190b685df944c372945","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# S1 Supervisor Contract\n\n_Status: v2 draft. Defines the canonical role, authority, workflow, and component boundaries of the S1 (Pre-Production) Supervisor._\n\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe S1 Supervisor is the canonical runtime brain for Pre-Production.\n\nIts job is to take a run that is `ready_for_s1` and coordinate the sector until it produces:\n- `screenplay.json`\n- `screenplay_validation.json`\n- `tts_polished.json`\n- `polish_validation.json`\n- `scene_bible.json`\n- `b1_*` checkpoints\n\nThe supervisor is an **OpenClaw LLM supervisor**.\nIt is not:\n- a purely conversational helper\n- a passive documentation artifact\n- a monolithic Python script that absorbs the whole sector itself\n\nThe canonical operating model for S1 is:\n- **`sm_s1_pre_production` = canonical runtime supervisor**\n- **OpenClaw operators = semantic specialists**\n- **deterministic Python components = execution substrate**\n- **persisted run artifacts = operational truth**\n\n---\n\n## Canonical runtime rule\n\nThe canonical runtime authority for S1 belongs to:\n- `sm_s1_pre_production`\n\nThis means the supervisor is the authoritative owner of:\n- sector sequencing\n- operator invocation decisions\n- validation interpretation\n- retry / fail / continue / escalate decisions\n- sector completion decisions\n\n### Important non-canonical component\n`runtime/s1/s1_start.py` must be treated as:\n- bootstrap layer\n- compatibility shim\n- transition helper\n- temporary orchestration bridge where still needed\n\nIt must **not** be treated as the long-term canonical brain of the sector.\n\nThe direction of travel is:\n- more authority in the OpenClaw supervisor\n- less sector intelligence embedded in `s1_start.py`\n\n---\n\n## Core principle\n\n### Supervisor = brain\n### Skills = hands\n### Operators = specialists\n### Persisted artifacts = truth\n\nThe S1 Supervisor should:\n- decide the order of operations\n- decide when to call an operator vs a deterministic component\n- interpret validation results\n- decide retry / fail / continue / escalate\n- decide when outputs are accepted into canonical artifacts\n- write or trigger checkpoints\n- determine final sector completion\n\nThe S1 Supervisor should **not** directly absorb:\n- semantic scene generation\n- TTS polish generation\n- low-level file/path mechanics\n- deterministic validation logic\n- JSON merge/reindex mechanics\n- scene bible construction internals\n\nThose belong to:\n- S1 operators\n- supervisor deterministic skills\n- shared deterministic sector components\n\n---\n\n## Component classes inside S1\n\nThe S1 sector is composed of four distinct component classes.\n\n### 1. Canonical supervisor\n- `sm_s1_pre_production`\n\n### 2. OpenClaw semantic operators\n- `scene_director`\n- `tts_polish`\n- `tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`\n\n### 3. Supervisor deterministic skills\nThese are deterministic components directly used by the supervisor to plan, bridge, validate, merge, schedule, and summarize the sector flow.\n\nImplemented now:\n- `s1_preflight_checker`\n- `s1_paths_resolver`\n- `script_batch_planner`\n- `scene_director_io_adapter`\n- `scene_director_output_validator`\n- `screenplay_merger`\n- `tts_polish_batch_planner`\n- `tts_polish_io_adapter`\n- `tts_polish_merger`\n- `retry_planner`\n- `operator_batch_scheduler`\n- `s1_result_summarizer`\n\n### 4. Shared deterministic sector components\nThese are deterministic runtime components used by the sector, but they are not supervisor-local planning/bridging skills.\n\nShared components currently used by S1:\n- `screenplay_validator`\n- `polish_validator`\n- `scene_bible_builder`\n- `scene_bible_schema_validator`\n- `checkpoint_writer`\n\nThis distinction is important:\n- supervisor skills shape supervision flow\n- shared deterministic components perform reusable sector mechanics\n\n---\n\n## File contract principle\n\nThe supervisor must operate on persisted run artifacts.\n\n### Minimum expected inputs before S1 begins\n- `job.json`\n- `run_metadata.json`\n- `inputs/script/script_raw.txt`\n- `inputs/script/script_metadata.json`\n- `inputs/script/script_lock.json`\n- `checkpoints/vo_script_ready.json`\n\n### Minimum expected outputs after S1 completes\n- `b1_pre_production/screenplay.json`\n- `b1_pre_production/screenplay_validation.json`\n- `b1_pre_production/tts_polished.json`\n- `b1_pre_production/polish_validation.json`\n- `scene_bible.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_step1_screenplay.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_step2_screenplay_validated.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_step3_tts_polished.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_step4_polish_validated.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_step5_scene_bible.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_complete.json`\n\nThe supervisor should reason over persisted artifacts rather than hidden in-memory assumptions.\n\n---\n\n## Naming convention\n\nThe canonical checkpoint and sector naming for Pre-Production is:\n- `b1_pre_production/`\n- `b1_*` checkpoints\n\nOlder `s1_*` naming is not canonical and should not be expanded further.\n\n---\n\n## Canonical authority map\n\n### Supervisor owns\n- sector order of operations\n- operator invocation decisions\n- acceptance/rejection of batch outputs\n- retry decisions\n- escalation decisions\n- final sector status\n\n### Operators own\n- semantic scene structuring (`scene_director`)\n- semantic TTS-oriented oral normalization (`tts_polish`)\n- semantic borderline review for polish when needed (`tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`)\n\n### Supervisor skills own\n- preflight\n- path resolution\n- batching\n- operator payload bridge construction\n- per-batch structural validation where defined\n- merge preparation/composition\n- controlled scheduling plans\n- retry recommendation logic\n- final result summarization\n\n### Shared deterministic components own\n- whole-screenplay validation\n- whole-polish validation\n- scene bible build\n- scene bible schema validation\n- checkpoint writing\n\n---\n\n## Canonical sector workflow\n\nThe canonical S1 flow is:\n\n1. Run `s1_preflight_checker`\n2. Run `s1_paths_resolver`\n3. Plan script batches via `script_batch_planner`\n4. Build `scene_director` payloads via `scene_director_io_adapter`\n5. Schedule `scene_director` batches via `operator_batch_scheduler`\n6. Invoke `scene_director` batches under supervisor control\n7. Validate each batch via `scene_director_output_validator`\n8. If needed, classify retry via `retry_planner`\n9. Merge approved batch outputs via `screenplay_merger`\n10. Validate canonical screenplay via `screenplay_validator`\n11. If screenplay validation fails, use `retry_planner`\n12. Plan polish batches via `tts_polish_batch_planner`\n13. Build `tts_polish` payloads via `tts_polish_io_adapter`\n14. Schedule `tts_polish` batches via `operator_batch_scheduler`\n15. Invoke `tts_polish` batches under supervisor control\n16. If needed, route borderline cases to `tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`\n17. Merge approved polish outputs via `tts_polish_merger`\n18. Validate canonical polish via `polish_validator`\n19. If polish validation fails, use `retry_planner`\n20. Build `scene_bible.json` via `scene_bible_builder`\n21. Validate scene bible schema via `scene_bible_schema_validator`\n22. Write/check checkpoints via `checkpoint_writer`\n23. Summarize the final result via `s1_result_summarizer`\n24. Complete or fail the sector\n\n---\n\n## Controlled parallelism policy\n\nThe S1 Supervisor should support controlled parallelism for batchable operators.\n\n### Initial concurrency caps\n- `scene_director_concurrency_cap = 2`\n- `tts_polish_concurrency_cap = 4`\n\n### Parallelism rules\n- only batchable operators should be parallelized\n- validators, mergers, builders, schema validation, checkpointing, and preflight remain sequential/deterministic\n- the supervisor should not launch all batches at once without a cap\n- batches should be processed in controlled waves/windows\n- failed batches should be retried selectively when possible\n\n### Important current limitation\n`operator_batch_scheduler` currently provides:\n- wave planning\n- concurrency capping\n- execution summary structure\n\nIt does **not** by itself invoke OpenClaw operators.\nThe supervisor still owns the actual invocation/control loop.\n\n---\n\n## Current operator model\n\nThe intended operator structure for S1 is:\n- `scene_director` -> OpenClaw operator\n- `tts_polish` -> OpenClaw operator\n- `tts_polish_semantic_reviewer` -> OpenClaw operator used only where semantic review is needed\n\nThese operators communicate with the supervisor via explicit file contracts:\n- supervisor prepares input payload/file\n- operator reads input\n- operator writes output file\n- supervisor validates and decides next step\n\nThe supervisor must not delegate its authority away.\nOperators are specialists, not sector owners.\n\n---\n\n## Supervisor deterministic skills\n\n## `s1_preflight_checker`\n\n### Purpose\nValidate that a run is structurally ready to enter S1 before any operator or semantic step is invoked.\n\n### Scope\nChecks:\n- run root exists\n- required input files exist\n- `job.json` is readable and contains `job_id`, `account`, `language`\n- channel config exists at `accounts/{account}/{language}.yaml`\n- `script_raw.txt` is readable and not empty\n- `vo_script_ready` checkpoint exists\n- run state is minimally compatible with entering S1\n\n### Out of scope\n- create sector outputs\n- call operators\n- validate screenplay semantics\n- decide batching\n- modify the run\n\n---\n\n## `s1_paths_resolver`\n\n### Purpose\nResolve and centralize the canonical S1 paths for the run.\n\n### Scope\nResolves and optionally creates the directory structure for:\n- `b1_pre_production/`\n- `b1_pre_production/inputs/`\n- `b1_pre_production/intermediate/`\n- `inputs/scene_director/`\n- `inputs/tts_polish/`\n- `intermediate/scene_director/`\n- `intermediate/tts_polish/`\n- canonical output file paths\n- canonical `b1_*` checkpoint file paths\n\n### Out of scope\n- validate semantic readiness\n- call operators\n- inspect screenplay or polish content\n- perform batching\n\n---\n\n## `script_batch_planner`\n\n### Purpose\nSplit the raw script into manageable work batches for `scene_director` without turning the supervisor into a monolithic batching script.\n\n### Scope\n- receives raw script text or script file path\n- plans batches using target/min/max word budgets\n- prefers paragraph boundaries\n- falls back to sentence-based splitting for oversized paragraphs\n- preserves order and emits a stable `sd_###` batch sequence\n\n### Out of scope\n- divide the script into final scenes\n- call `scene_director`\n- perform semantic validation\n- merge operator outputs\n\n### Recommended v1 defaults\n- target words per batch: `750`\n- minimum words per batch: `450`\n- maximum words per batch: `950`\n\n---\n\n## `scene_director_io_adapter`\n\n### Purpose\nPrepare the explicit input/output contract between the S1 Supervisor and the `scene_director` operator for each planned script batch.\n\n### Scope\n- receives run/job context\n- receives one script batch from `script_batch_planner`\n- injects `scene_words_range` from channel config\n- writes a deterministic payload file for the operator\n- declares the expected output path for the batch result\n\n### Out of scope\n- run the operator\n- validate semantic quality\n- merge batch outputs\n- choose retry policy\n\n### Contract note\nThis component is an interface-critical bridge and should have its own dedicated contract.\n\n---\n\n## `scene_director_output_validator`\n\n### Purpose\nValidate each `scene_director` batch output independently before any merge into canonical `screenplay.json` happens.\n\n### Scope\n- validate output shape for one batch result\n- validate required scene fields\n- validate `scene_local_id` ordering/sequencing\n- validate scene span ordering and non-overlap\n- validate coverage of the intended batch source span\n- validate that `narration_original` matches the source text assigned to each scene\n- classify failures for supervisor retry handling\n\n### Out of scope\n- merge batches\n- decide final retry policy by itself\n- rewrite operator outputs directly\n- judge creative quality beyond deterministic structural/fidelity checks\n\n### Contract note\nThis component is an acceptance gate and should have its own dedicated contract.\n\n---\n\n## `screenplay_merger`\n\n### Purpose\nMerge the batch outputs of `scene_director` into one canonical `screenplay.json`.\n\n### Scope\n- loads ordered batch output files\n- validates minimum required scene fields\n- concatenates scenes in batch order\n- reassigns canonical `scene_###` IDs globally\n- writes `screenplay.json`\n\n### Out of scope\n- perform semantic validation\n- decide retry policy\n- invoke operators\n- polish TTS text\n\n### Contract note\nThis component writes a canonical sector artifact and should have its own dedicated contract.\n\n---\n\n## `tts_polish_batch_planner`\n\n### Purpose\nPlan small, stable polish batches from the merged screenplay so that `tts_polish` receives manageable groups of scenes instead of the full screenplay at once.\n\n### Scope\n- receives `screenplay.json`\n- groups scenes by count and approximate word budget\n- preserves scene order\n- emits a stable `tp_###` batch sequence\n\n### Recommended v1 defaults\n- target scenes per batch: `5`\n- minimum scenes per batch: `3`\n- maximum scenes per batch: `6`\n- maximum words per batch: `350`\n\n### Out of scope\n- perform TTS polish\n- validate semantic quality\n- merge polish outputs\n- decide retry policy\n\n---\n\n## `tts_polish_io_adapter`\n\n### Purpose\nPrepare the explicit input/output contract between the S1 Supervisor and the `tts_polish` operator for each planned polish batch.\n\n### Scope\n- receives run/job context\n- receives merged screenplay\n- receives one polish batch from `tts_polish_batch_planner`\n- injects `tts_polish_rules` from channel config\n- writes a deterministic payload file for the operator\n- declares the expected output path for the batch result\n\n### Out of scope\n- run the operator\n- validate semantic quality\n- merge polish outputs\n- choose retry policy\n\n### Contract note\nThis component is an interface-critical bridge and should have its own dedicated contract.\n\n---\n\n## `tts_polish_merger`\n\n### Purpose\nMerge the batch outputs of `tts_polish` into one canonical `tts_polished.json` while preserving screenplay order and preserving the distinction between original narration and TTS-polished narration.\n\n### Scope\n- loads ordered polish batch files\n- validates minimum required polish scene fields\n- rebuilds one ordered `tts_polished.json`\n- uses screenplay order as the canonical scene sequence\n\n### Out of scope\n- validate semantic quality of the polish\n- decide retry policy\n- invoke operators\n- overwrite the original screenplay artifact\n\n### Contract note\nThis component writes a canonical sector artifact and should have its own dedicated contract.\n\n---\n\n## `retry_planner`\n\n### Purpose\nTurn observed failures into explicit retry decisions so the S1 Supervisor can decide whether to abort, rerun a whole step, or rerun only affected batches.\n\n### Scope\n- classifies failure types into retry strategies\n- enforces retry limits\n- supports fail-fast structural errors\n- supports batch-subset retries for localized operator/semantic failures\n- supports step-level retries when failures are broader\n\n### Out of scope\n- run retries itself\n- inspect semantic payloads deeply\n- invoke operators or validators\n- write checkpoints\n\n### Decision categories in v1\n- `abort`\n- `step`\n- `batch_subset`\n\n### Contract note\nThis component encodes sector recovery policy and should have its own dedicated contract.\n\n---\n\n## `operator_batch_scheduler`\n\n### Purpose\nProvide the controlled parallelism layer for batchable operators so the supervisor can launch work in capped waves instead of all-at-once or fully sequentially.\n\n### Scope\n- receives operator batches\n- applies a concurrency cap\n- groups batches into execution waves\n- summarizes execution outcomes into completed / failed / pending sets\n\n### Initial supported operators\n- `scene_director`\n- `tts_polish`\n\n### Out of scope\n- invoke OpenClaw operators by itself\n- decide semantic retry logic\n- merge outputs\n- validate content\n\n### Contract note\nThis component defines operational scheduling semantics and should have its own dedicated contract.\n\n---\n\n## `s1_result_summarizer`\n\n### Purpose\nProduce the final structured sector result that the S1 Supervisor can return upward after the sector finishes or fails.\n\n### Scope\n- aggregates scene counts\n- aggregates batch counts\n- exposes `scene_bible_path`\n- exposes checkpoint list\n- determines final `status` / `next_step`\n- preserves warnings/errors in one final result object\n\n### Out of scope\n- run the sector\n- write checkpoints\n- validate semantic correctness\n- call operators or skills\n\n---\n\n## Shared deterministic sector components\n\nThese components are used by S1 but are not classified as supervisor-local skills:\n- `screenplay_validator`\n- `polish_validator`\n- `scene_bible_builder`\n- `scene_bible_schema_validator`\n- `checkpoint_writer`\n\nThese should remain documented as shared sector components and not be confused with semantic operators or with the supervisor brain itself.\n\n---\n\n## Contract coverage guidance\n\n### Components that should have dedicated contracts\n- `scene_director_io_adapter`\n- `scene_director_output_validator`\n- `screenplay_merger`\n- `tts_polish_io_adapter`\n- `tts_polish_merger`\n- `retry_planner`\n- `operator_batch_scheduler`\n\n### Components that may remain documented primarily inside this supervisor contract for now\n- `s1_preflight_checker`\n- `s1_paths_resolver`\n- `script_batch_planner`\n- `tts_polish_batch_planner`\n- `s1_result_summarizer`\n\n### Components that should be documented as shared deterministic sector components\n- `screenplay_validator`\n- `polish_validator`\n- `scene_bible_builder`\n- `scene_bible_schema_validator`\n- `checkpoint_writer`\n\nDedicated shared deterministic contracts should exist for:\n- `screenplay_validator`\n- `polish_validator`\n- `scene_bible_builder`\n- `scene_bible_schema_validator`\n\n---\n\n## Current status summary\n\nAt this stage:\n- the S1 Supervisor is defined as the canonical OpenClaw runtime brain for the sector\n- the component classes inside S1 are now explicitly separated\n- the intended authority of the supervisor vs operators vs deterministic components is explicit\n- `scene_director` flow is structurally well-defined from batch planning through validation and merge\n- `tts_polish` flow is structurally defined, including the existence of a semantic reviewer lane for borderline cases\n- controlled operator parallelism is defined at the planning/supervisory level\n- `s1_start.py` is explicitly demoted from canonical sector brain to bootstrap/transition role\n\nThe remaining work is no longer to invent the S1 architecture, but to ensure every agent, contract, workspace, and deterministic component is fully aligned with this canonical model.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775047880295}}
{"type":"message","id":"783d1e49","parentId":"b6a27b6f","timestamp":"2026-04-01T12:51:20.663Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_2TiLoxH2wzB6RQGPSTNOyFfD|fc_0785557c08065f410169cd14c80238819083598c8eb400892e","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# runtime/s1\n\n## Status\n\nThis directory currently contains **two coexisting layers**:\n\n### 1. Canonical S1 architecture (target / active consolidation path)\n- `supervisor_skills/`\n- `screenplay_validator.py`\n- `polish_validator.py`\n- `scene_bible_builder.py`\n- `scene_bible_schema_validator.py`\n- `checkpoint_writer.py`\n\nThis is the architecture aligned with:\n- `sm_s1_pre_production`\n- OpenClaw operators\n- explicit contracts in `docs/contracts/s1/`\n\n### 2. Legacy transitional compatibility path\n- `s1_start.py`\n- `scene_director_runner.py`\n- `tts_polish_runner.py`\n\nThese files are still present because:\n- legacy tests depend on them\n- they provide a prototype linear execution path\n- they have not yet been fully retired from the repo\n\nThey should **not** be treated as the canonical long-term runtime design for S1.\n\n## Cleanup policy\n\n### Safe to keep\n- canonical supervisor skills\n- shared deterministic sector components\n- legacy transitional files only while imports/tests still depend on them\n\n### Safe to remove\n- `__pycache__/`\n\n### Do not remove yet without migration\n- `s1_start.py`\n- `scene_director_runner.py`\n- `tts_polish_runner.py`\n\n## Direction of travel\n\nThe intended end state is:\n- OpenClaw supervisor as sector brain\n- OpenClaw operators as semantic specialists\n- deterministic Python substrate as support layer\n- legacy prototype path either removed or isolated only after dependency migration\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775047880479}}
{"type":"message","id":"fd5b6d36","parentId":"783d1e49","timestamp":"2026-04-01T12:51:20.845Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_xZ2kap9YrVjqmzQgiTF6Owa0|fc_0785557c08065f410169cd14c802448190a0b0fae9fc295339","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\"\"\"S1 Supervisor Runtime — canonical execution substrate for SM-S1.\n\nThis module is the execution substrate for the canonical S1 architecture.\nIt is intended to support the OpenClaw supervisor (`sm_s1_pre_production`) as the\nruntime brain of the sector.\n\nIt is NOT the legacy linear prototype path from `runtime.s1.s1_start`.\n\nDesign goal:\n- supervisor owns sequencing / acceptance / retry / completion decisions\n- deterministic skills and shared components perform mechanical work\n- OpenClaw operators perform semantic work\n- persisted artifacts remain operational truth\n\nInvocation strategy note:\n- canonical operator invocation should ultimately be performed through a real\n  OpenClaw runtime bridge\n- until a richer in-process bridge exists, this module may use an explicit\n  transitional adapter boundary for CLI/operator invocation\n- the adapter boundary is kept narrow on purpose so the architecture stays clear\n\nCurrent status:\n- scaffold / skeleton only\n- lane decomposition established\n- operator invocation hooks intentionally left explicit and narrow\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport json\nimport shutil\nimport subprocess\nfrom pathlib import Path\nfrom typing import Any\n\nimport yaml\n\nfrom runtime.s1.checkpoint_writer import write_checkpoint\nfrom runtime.s1.polish_validator import validate_polish\nfrom runtime.s1.scene_bible_builder import build_scene_bible, write_scene_bible\nfrom runtime.s1.scene_bible_schema_validator import validate_scene_bible_schema\nfrom runtime.s1.screenplay_validator import validate_screenplay\nfrom runtime.s1.supervisor_skills.operator_batch_scheduler import (\n    build_batch_schedule,\n    summarize_batch_execution,\n)\nfrom runtime.s1.supervisor_skills.retry_planner import plan_retry\nfrom runtime.s1.supervisor_skills.s1_paths_resolver import resolve_paths\nfrom runtime.s1.supervisor_skills.s1_preflight_checker import run_preflight\nfrom runtime.s1.supervisor_skills.s1_result_summarizer import summarize_s1_result\nfrom runtime.s1.supervisor_skills.scene_director_io_adapter import write_scene_director_payload\nfrom runtime.s1.supervisor_skills.scene_director_output_validator import validate_scene_director_output\nfrom runtime.s1.supervisor_skills.screenplay_merger import merge_screenplay_batches\nfrom runtime.s1.supervisor_skills.script_batch_planner import plan_script_batches_from_file\nfrom runtime.s1.supervisor_skills.tts_polish_batch_planner import plan_tts_polish_batches\nfrom runtime.s1.supervisor_skills.tts_polish_io_adapter import write_tts_polish_payload\nfrom runtime.s1.supervisor_skills.tts_polish_merger import merge_tts_polish_batches\nfrom runtime.s1.supervisor_skills.tts_polish_output_validator import validate_tts_polish_output\n\n\nACCOUNTS_DIR = Path(__file__).parent.parent.parent / \"accounts\"\nDEFAULT_SCENE_DIRECTOR_CONCURRENCY = 2\nDEFAULT_TTS_POLISH_CONCURRENCY = 4\nDEFAULT_MAX_RETRIES = 3\n\n\ndef run_s1_supervisor_runtime(\n    *,\n    run_root: str | Path,\n    job: dict[str, Any] | None = None,\n    channel_config: dict[str, Any] | None = None,\n    model: str = \"gpt-4.1-mini\",\n    max_retries: int = DEFAULT_MAX_RETRIES,\n) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    \"\"\"Canonical execution substrate for S1 under supervisor authority.\n\n    This function intentionally decomposes the sector into lanes that map to the\n    canonical OpenClaw architecture.\n\n    Important:\n    - this module is the execution substrate, not the supervisor brain itself\n    - decision sovereignty still belongs to the supervisor layer\n    - operator invocation is left behind explicit hooks to avoid hiding architecture\n    \"\"\"\n    run_root = Path(run_root)\n    checkpoints_written: list[str] = []\n    all_warnings: list[dict[str, Any]] = []\n    all_errors: list[dict[str, Any]] = []\n\n    preflight = run_preflight(run_root)\n    if not preflight.get(\"ok\"):\n        return _failed_result(run_root, preflight.get(\"errors\", []), preflight.get(\"warnings\", []))\n    all_warnings.extend(preflight.get(\"warnings\", []))\n\n    if job is None:\n        job = preflight.get(\"job\", {})\n\n    account = job.get(\"account\")\n    language = job.get(\"language\")\n    if channel_config is None:\n        channel_config = _load_config(account, language)\n\n    paths_result = resolve_paths(run_root, create_dirs=True)\n    paths = paths_result.get(\"paths\", {})\n    all_warnings.extend(paths_result.get(\"warnings\", []))\n\n    script_path = Path(preflight[\"paths\"][\"script_raw\"])\n    script_raw = script_path.read_text(encoding=\"utf-8\")\n\n    screenplay_lane = _run_scene_director_lane(\n        run_root=run_root,\n        job=job,\n        channel_config=channel_config,\n        paths=paths,\n        script_path=script_path,\n        script_raw=script_raw,\n        model=model,\n        max_retries=max_retries,\n    )\n    all_warnings.extend(screenplay_lane.get(\"warnings\", []))\n\n[717 more lines in file. Use offset=121 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775047880479}}
{"type":"message","id":"cd88aba8","parentId":"fd5b6d36","timestamp":"2026-04-01T12:52:28.379Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_RFIvVdWcGhNOCtzOJEOqcVib|fc_0785557c08065f410169cd14cfc10c819095270b4a1cac3335","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\implementation\\s1\\S1_IMPLEMENTATION_STATUS.md","content":"# S1_IMPLEMENTATION_STATUS.md\n\n_Status: active implementation checkpoint_\n\n_Last updated: 2026-04-01_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThis document captures the **real implementation status** of S1 (Pre-Production) as of the current OpenClaw migration effort.\n\nIt is not meant to replace the contracts under `docs/contracts/s1/`.\nIts role is to answer:\n- what is canonical now\n- what is transitional/legacy now\n- what is already implemented\n- what has been materially validated\n- what still remains before S1 should be called fully done\n\n---\n\n## Executive summary\n\nS1 is no longer in the phase of vague architecture or loose prototype-only thinking.\n\nAs of this checkpoint, S1 is best described as:\n\n> **integration-ready, pending final upstream/runtime validation**\n\nThat means:\n- the canonical runtime direction is clear\n- the canonical supervisor exists conceptually and operationally\n- the runtime substrate is materially implemented\n- the main S1 operators exist as real OpenClaw workspaces/agents\n- deterministic validation/merge/build layers are much more coherent\n- tests are green\n\nBut it also means:\n- S1 should still ideally be validated inside the real upstream flow (`PM -> VO -> S1`)\n- it should not yet be treated as metaphysically final just because tests are green\n\n---\n\n## Canonical authority\n\n### Canonical supervisor\n- `sm_s1_pre_production`\n\nThe canonical runtime authority for S1 belongs to the OpenClaw supervisor layer, not to a legacy linear Python orchestration entrypoint.\n\n### Core principle\n- supervisor = brain\n- operators = semantic specialists\n- deterministic Python components = execution substrate\n- persisted artifacts = operational truth\n\nThis authority split is now explicit in the implementation and in the contracts.\n\n---\n\n## Canonical runtime implementation\n\n### Main canonical execution substrate\n- `runtime/s1/supervisor_runtime.py`\n\nThis is the implementation file that currently expresses the intended canonical runtime shape of S1.\n\n### Main lanes modeled there\n- `scene_director`\n- `tts_polish`\n- `scene_bible`\n\n### Current runtime shape\nThe runtime currently performs, in canonical form:\n1. preflight validation\n2. path resolution\n3. batch planning\n4. payload creation for operators\n5. operator invocation\n6. batch validation\n7. merge\n8. whole-artifact validation\n9. scene bible generation\n10. checkpoint writing\n11. structured result summarization\n\n---\n\n## Operator invocation strategy\n\nA major implementation clarification has already happened:\n\n### Wrong earlier hypothesis\n- `openclaw agents` was briefly treated as if it were an execution surface\n\n### Correct current direction\nThe correct runtime invocation surface is:\n- `openclaw agent`\n\nThis matters because the S1 runtime bridge now aligns with the real OpenClaw execution model instead of a mistaken registry/config assumption.\n\n### Current bridge style\nThe canonical runtime still uses a **transitional CLI invocation boundary** to call the operators.\n\nThat means:\n- explicit payload file path\n- explicit output file path\n- operator reads payload\n- operator writes artifact\n- supervisor validates before merge\n\nThis is intentionally narrow and explicit.\n\n---\n\n## Current S1 component map\n\n### Canonical OpenClaw supervisor\n- `sm_s1_pre_production`\n\n### OpenClaw semantic operators\n- `op_s1_scene_director`\n- `op_s1_tts_polish`\n- `op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`\n\n### Supervisor-local deterministic skills\nKey currently implemented/used pieces include:\n- `s1_preflight_checker`\n- `s1_paths_resolver`\n- `script_batch_planner`\n- `scene_director_io_adapter`\n- `scene_director_output_validator`\n- `screenplay_merger`\n- `tts_polish_batch_planner`\n- `tts_polish_io_adapter`\n- `tts_polish_output_validator`\n- `tts_polish_merger`\n- `retry_planner`\n- `operator_batch_scheduler`\n- `s1_result_summarizer`\n\n### Shared deterministic sector components\n- `screenplay_validator`\n- `polish_validator`\n- `scene_bible_builder`\n- `scene_bible_schema_validator`\n- `checkpoint_writer`\n\n---\n\n## Legacy vs canonical runtime layers\n\nThe repo still contains two coexisting layers.\n\n### Canonical / active consolidation path\nLocated mainly in:\n- `runtime/s1/supervisor_runtime.py`\n- `runtime/s1/supervisor_skills/`\n- shared validators/builders/writers under `runtime/s1/`\n\n### Legacy transitional compatibility path\nStill present in:\n- `runtime/s1/s1_start.py`\n- `runtime/s1/scene_director_runner.py`\n- `runtime/s1/tts_polish_runner.py`\n\n### Important rule\nThese legacy files should **not** be treated as the long-term canonical runtime design for S1.\n\nThey remain in the repo only because:\n- compatibility still matters\n- some legacy tests/imports still depend on them\n- migration is incremental rather than destructive\n\n---\n\n## File contract expectations\n\n### Minimum expected inputs before S1 begins\n- `job.json`\n- `run_metadata.json`\n- `inputs/script/script_raw.txt`\n- `inputs/script/script_metadata.json`\n- `inputs/script/script_lock.json`\n- `checkpoints/vo_script_ready.json`\n\n### Minimum expected outputs after S1 completes\n- `b1_pre_production/screenplay.json`\n- `b1_pre_production/screenplay_validation.json`\n- `b1_pre_production/tts_polished.json`\n- `b1_pre_production/polish_validation.json`\n- `scene_bible.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_step1_screenplay.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_step2_screenplay_validated.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_step3_tts_polished.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_step4_polish_validated.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_step5_scene_bible.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_complete.json`\n\n---\n\n## Current implementation status by lane\n\n## `scene_director`\n\n### Status\nStrong.\n\n### What is materially true now\n- the operator workspace exists\n- file-based payload/output flow has been validated\n- per-batch validation exists\n- canonical merge path exists\n- screenplay-level validation exists\n\n### Confidence\nHigh.\n\nThis lane is no longer the main unknown in S1.\n\n---\n\n## `tts_polish`\n\n### Status\nMuch stronger than before, but historically the more sensitive lane.\n\n### What was improved recently\n- runtime invocation hook wired in canonical runtime\n- worker discipline of `op_s1_tts_polish` reinforced\n- explicit per-batch `tts_polish_output_validator` introduced\n- whole-polish validation aligned to canonical `narration_original` / `narration_tts` shape\n- validator policy reduced in excessive conservatism for safe TTS equivalences\n\n### Practical meaning\nThis lane is no longer a conceptual placeholder.\nIt is part of the real canonical runtime story now.\n\n### Remaining caution\nIt is still the lane most likely to expose subtle issues once upstream integration starts feeding it real runs.\n\n---\n\n## `scene_bible`\n\n### Status\nStructurally strong.\n\n### What is materially true now\n- scene bible build path exists\n- schema validation exists\n- canonical placement is clear (`scene_bible.json` at run root)\n\nThis lane is currently less controversial than the TTS lane.\n\n---\n\n## Tests and fixtures status\n\n### Current test state\n- tests are green (`176/176` at the latest checkpoint)\n\n### Why this matters\nA major part of the recent stabilization work was not “inventing more architecture”, but aligning the implementation world with the real canonical schema.\n\n### What had to be corrected\nFixtures/tests had lagged behind the canonical field model. In practical terms, the migration required aligning test/fixture expectations with:\n- `narration_original`\n- `narration_tts`\n\nThis reduced false confusion where code and tests were effectively speaking slightly different dialects.\n\n### Important nuance\nGreen tests are strong evidence of consistency.\nThey are not yet, by themselves, the final proof of full production-readiness in upstream-integrated runtime.\n\n---\n\n## OpenClaw workspace/agent reality\n\nThe S1 work did not remain purely repo-doc level.\nReal OpenClaw workspaces/agents were also aligned for the S1 layer.\n\nThis matters because the migration effort is not only:\n- updating contracts\n- updating Python runtime files\n\nIt is also:\n- aligning the actual OpenClaw operator workspaces\n- ensuring their runtime worker behavior matches the canonical batch contract\n\nThis is especially important for:\n- `op_s1_scene_director`\n- `op_s1_tts_polish`\n\n---\n\n## What is already materially validated\n\nAt this point, the strongest claims we can make are:\n- S1 canonical direction is explicit and stable\n- supervisor authority is explicit\n- legacy vs canonical boundary is explicit\n- operators are real and aligned more closely to the intended worker model\n- deterministic substrate is materially more coherent\n- tests are green\n- S1 is ready to be treated as the first serious integration target upstream\n\n---\n\n## What is not yet wise to claim without qualification\n\nIt is still too strong to say:\n- “S1 is absolutely final in every production sense”\n- “S1 never needs another runtime adjustment”\n- “upstream integration cannot reveal new bugs”\n\nThe honest status is still:\n- **integration-ready**\n- **not yet beyond all doubt**\n\n---\n\n## What remains before calling S1 fully done\n\n### Recommended remaining proof steps\n1. run the canonical S1 path with real upstream-shaped input\n2. inspect real produced artifacts, not only passing tests\n3. confirm behavior inside the real upstream flow:\n   - `PM -> VO -> S1`\n\n### Why this matters\nThe next meaningful class of failures is more likely to come from integration boundaries than from isolated internal S1 design.\n\nExamples:\n- malformed upstream job/run artifacts\n- handoff assumptions between PM/VO and S1\n- path/checkpoint/state mismatches in realistic pipeline conditions\n\n---\n\n## Immediate strategic implication\n\nThe next highest-value move is not endless isolated polishing of S1.\n\nIt is:\n- freeze S1 as sufficiently mature for integration\n- move into operational diagnosis of PM and VO\n- turn PM and VO into real OpenClaw agents/workspaces where needed\n- configure PM and VO for `gpt-5.4-mini`\n- push toward a controlled `PM -> VO -> S1` validation path\n\n---\n\n## Relationship to contracts and workspace docs\n\nThis file should be read together with:\n- `docs/contracts/s1/` for the formal contracts\n- workspace/agent operational docs for the real OpenClaw runtime behavior\n\nThis file is specifically the **bridge between architecture and implementation reality**.\n\n---\n\n## Final summary\n\nS1 is now in a materially better place than it was during the earlier architecture-only phase.\n\nIt has:\n- canonical supervisory authority\n- a real runtime substrate\n- aligned operators\n- stronger validators/mergers/builders\n- clear legacy boundaries\n- green tests\n\nThe remaining work is no longer primarily “invent S1”.\nIt is:\n- validate S1 under real upstream integration pressure\n- then move the rest of the pipeline to the same standard.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\docs\\\\implementation\\\\s1\\\\S1_IMPLEMENTATION_STATUS.md\",\"content\":\"# S1_IMPLEMENTATION_STATUS.md\\n\\n_Status: active implementation checkpoint_\\n\\n_Last updated: 2026-04-01_\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Purpose\\n\\nThis document captures the **real implementation status** of S1 (Pre-Production) as of the current OpenClaw migration effort.\\n\\nIt is not meant to replace the contracts under `docs/contracts/s1/`.\\nIts role is to answer:\\n- what is canonical now\\n- what is transitional/legacy now\\n- what is already implemented\\n- what has been materially validated\\n- what still remains before S1 should be called fully done\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Executive summary\\n\\nS1 is no longer in the phase of vague architecture or loose prototype-only thinking.\\n\\nAs of this checkpoint, S1 is best described as:\\n\\n> **integration-ready, pending final upstream/runtime validation**\\n\\nThat means:\\n- the canonical runtime direction is clear\\n- the canonical supervisor exists conceptually and operationally\\n- the runtime substrate is materially implemented\\n- the main S1 operators exist as real OpenClaw workspaces/agents\\n- deterministic validation/merge/build layers are much more coherent\\n- tests are green\\n\\nBut it also means:\\n- S1 should still ideally be validated inside the real upstream flow (`PM -> VO -> S1`)\\n- it should not yet be treated as metaphysically final just because tests are green\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Canonical authority\\n\\n### Canonical supervisor\\n- `sm_s1_pre_production`\\n\\nThe canonical runtime authority for S1 belongs to the OpenClaw supervisor layer, not to a legacy linear Python orchestration entrypoint.\\n\\n### Core principle\\n- supervisor = brain\\n- operators = semantic specialists\\n- deterministic Python components = execution substrate\\n- persisted artifacts = operational truth\\n\\nThis authority split is now explicit in the implementation and in the contracts.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Canonical runtime implementation\\n\\n### Main canonical execution substrate\\n- `runtime/s1/supervisor_runtime.py`\\n\\nThis is the implementation file that currently expresses the intended canonical runtime shape of S1.\\n\\n### Main lanes modeled there\\n- `scene_director`\\n- `tts_polish`\\n- `scene_bible`\\n\\n### Current runtime shape\\nThe runtime currently performs, in canonical form:\\n1. preflight validation\\n2. path resolution\\n3. batch planning\\n4. payload creation for operators\\n5. operator invocation\\n6. batch validation\\n7. merge\\n8. whole-artifact validation\\n9. scene bible generation\\n10. checkpoint writing\\n11. structured result summarization\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Operator invocation strategy\\n\\nA major implementation clarification has already happened:\\n\\n### Wrong earlier hypothesis\\n- `openclaw agents` was briefly treated as if it were an execution surface\\n\\n### Correct current direction\\nThe correct runtime invocation surface is:\\n- `openclaw agent`\\n\\nThis matters because the S1 runtime bridge now aligns with the real OpenClaw execution model instead of a mistaken registry/config assumption.\\n\\n### Current bridge style\\nThe canonical runtime still uses a **transitional CLI invocation boundary** to call the operators.\\n\\nThat means:\\n- explicit payload file path\\n- explicit output file path\\n- operator reads payload\\n- operator writes artifact\\n- supervisor validates before merge\\n\\nThis is intentionally narrow and explicit.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Current S1 component map\\n\\n### Canonical OpenClaw supervisor\\n- `sm_s1_pre_production`\\n\\n### OpenClaw semantic operators\\n- `op_s1_scene_director`\\n- `op_s1_tts_polish`\\n- `op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`\\n\\n### Supervisor-local deterministic skills\\nKey currently implemented/used pieces include:\\n- `s1_preflight_checker`\\n- `s1_paths_resolver`\\n- `script_batch_planner`\\n- `scene_director_io_adapter`\\n- `scene_director_output_validator`\\n- `screenplay_merger`\\n- `tts_polish_batch_planner`\\n- `tts_polish_io_adapter`\\n- `tts_polish_output_validator`\\n- `tts_polish_merger`\\n- `retry_planner`\\n- `operator_batch_scheduler`\\n- `s1_result_summarizer`\\n\\n### Shared deterministic sector components\\n- `screenplay_validator`\\n- `polish_validator`\\n- `scene_bible_builder`\\n- `scene_bible_schema_validator`\\n- `checkpoint_writer`\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Legacy vs canonical runtime layers\\n\\nThe repo still contains two coexisting layers.\\n\\n### Canonical / active consolidation path\\nLocated mainly in:\\n- `runtime/s1/supervisor_runtime.py`\\n- `runtime/s1/supervisor_skills/`\\n- shared validators/builders/writers under `runtime/s1/`\\n\\n### Legacy transitional compatibility path\\nStill present in:\\n- `runtime/s1/s1_start.py`\\n- `runtime/s1/scene_director_runner.py`\\n- `runtime/s1/tts_polish_runner.py`\\n\\n### Important rule\\nThese legacy files should **not** be treated as the long-term canonical runtime design for S1.\\n\\nThey remain in the repo only because:\\n- compatibility still matters\\n- some legacy tests/imports still depend on them\\n- migration is incremental rather than destructive\\n\\n---\\n\\n## File contract expectations\\n\\n### Minimum expected inputs before S1 begins\\n- `job.json`\\n- `run_metadata.json`\\n- `inputs/script/script_raw.txt`\\n- `inputs/script/script_metadata.json`\\n- `inputs/script/script_lock.json`\\n- `checkpoints/vo_script_ready.json`\\n\\n### Minimum expected outputs after S1 completes\\n- `b1_pre_production/screenplay.json`\\n- `b1_pre_production/screenplay_validation.json`\\n- `b1_pre_production/tts_polished.json`\\n- `b1_pre_production/polish_validation.json`\\n- `scene_bible.json`\\n- `checkpoints/b1_step1_screenplay.json`\\n- `checkpoints/b1_step2_screenplay_validated.json`\\n- `checkpoints/b1_step3_tts_polished.json`\\n- `checkpoints/b1_step4_polish_validated.json`\\n- `checkpoints/b1_step5_scene_bible.json`\\n- `checkpoints/b1_complete.json`\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Current implementation status by lane\\n\\n## `scene_director`\\n\\n### Status\\nStrong.\\n\\n### What is materially true now\\n- the operator workspace exists\\n- file-based payload/output flow has been validated\\n- per-batch validation exists\\n- canonical merge path exists\\n- screenplay-level validation exists\\n\\n### Confidence\\nHigh.\\n\\nThis lane is no longer the main unknown in S1.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## `tts_polish`\\n\\n### Status\\nMuch stronger than before, but historically the more sensitive lane.\\n\\n### What was improved recently\\n- runtime invocation hook wired in canonical runtime\\n- worker discipline of `op_s1_tts_polish` reinforced\\n- explicit per-batch `tts_polish_output_validator` introduced\\n- whole-polish validation aligned to canonical `narration_original` / `narration_tts` shape\\n- validator policy reduced in excessive conservatism for safe TTS equivalences\\n\\n### Practical meaning\\nThis lane is no longer a conceptual placeholder.\\nIt is part of the real canonical runtime story now.\\n\\n### Remaining caution\\nIt is still the lane most likely to expose subtle issues once upstream integration starts feeding it real runs.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## `scene_bible`\\n\\n### Status\\nStructurally strong.\\n\\n### What is materially true now\\n- scene bible build path exists\\n- schema validation exists\\n- canonical placement is clear (`scene_bible.json` at run root)\\n\\nThis lane is currently less controversial than the TTS lane.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Tests and fixtures status\\n\\n### Current test state\\n- tests are green (`176/176` at the latest checkpoint)\\n\\n### Why this matters\\nA major part of the recent stabilization work was not “inventing more architecture”, but aligning the implementation world with the real canonical schema.\\n\\n### What had to be corrected\\nFixtures/tests had lagged behind the canonical field model. In practical terms, the migration required aligning test/fixture expectations with:\\n- `narration_original`\\n- `narration_tts`\\n\\nThis reduced false confusion where code and tests were effectively speaking slightly different dialects.\\n\\n### Important nuance\\nGreen tests are strong evidence of consistency.\\nThey are not yet, by themselves, the final proof of full production-readiness in upstream-integrated runtime.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## OpenClaw workspace/agent reality\\n\\nThe S1 work did not remain purely repo-doc level.\\nReal OpenClaw workspaces/agents were also aligned for the S1 layer.\\n\\nThis matters because the migration effort is not only:\\n- updating contracts\\n- updating Python runtime files\\n\\nIt is also:\\n- aligning the actual OpenClaw operator workspaces\\n- ensuring their runtime worker behavior matches the canonical batch contract\\n\\nThis is especially important for:\\n- `op_s1_scene_director`\\n- `op_s1_tts_polish`\\n\\n---\\n\\n## What is already materially validated\\n\\nAt this point, the strongest claims we can make are:\\n- S1 canonical direction is explicit and stable\\n- supervisor authority is explicit\\n- legacy vs canonical boundary is explicit\\n- operators are real and aligned more closely to the intended worker model\\n- deterministic substrate is materially more coherent\\n- tests are green\\n- S1 is ready to be treated as the first serious integration target upstream\\n\\n---\\n\\n## What is not yet wise to claim without qualification\\n\\nIt is still too strong to say:\\n- “S1 is absolutely final in every production sense”\\n- “S1 never needs another runtime adjustment”\\n- “upstream integration cannot reveal new bugs”\\n\\nThe honest status is still:\\n- **integration-ready**\\n- **not yet beyond all doubt**\\n\\n---\\n\\n## What remains before calling S1 fully done\\n\\n### Recommended remaining proof steps\\n1. run the canonical S1 path with real upstream-shaped input\\n2. inspect real produced artifacts, not only passing tests\\n3. confirm behavior inside the real upstream flow:\\n   - `PM -> VO -> S1`\\n\\n### Why this matters\\nThe next meaningful class of failures is more likely to come from integration boundaries than from isolated internal S1 design.\\n\\nExamples:\\n- malformed upstream job/run artifacts\\n- handoff assumptions between PM/VO and S1\\n- path/checkpoint/state mismatches in realistic pipeline conditions\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Immediate strategic implication\\n\\nThe next highest-value move is not endless isolated polishing of S1.\\n\\nIt is:\\n- freeze S1 as sufficiently mature for integration\\n- move into operational diagnosis of PM and VO\\n- turn PM and VO into real OpenClaw agents/workspaces where needed\\n- configure PM and VO for `gpt-5.4-mini`\\n- push toward a controlled `PM -> VO -> S1` validation path\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Relationship to contracts and workspace docs\\n\\nThis file should be read together with:\\n- `docs/contracts/s1/` for the formal contracts\\n- workspace/agent operational docs for the real OpenClaw runtime behavior\\n\\nThis file is specifically the **bridge between architecture and implementation reality**.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Final summary\\n\\nS1 is now in a materially better place than it was during the earlier architecture-only phase.\\n\\nIt has:\\n- canonical supervisory authority\\n- a real runtime substrate\\n- aligned operators\\n- stronger validators/mergers/builders\\n- clear legacy boundaries\\n- green tests\\n\\nThe remaining work is no longer primarily “invent S1”.\\nIt is:\\n- validate S1 under real upstream integration pressure\\n- then move the rest of the pipeline to the same standard.\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":121473,"output":2651,"cacheRead":20992,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":145116,"cost":{"input":0.3036825,"output":0.039765,"cacheRead":0.005248,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.3486955}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775047881394,"responseId":"resp_0785557c08065f410169cd14cb7bf88190ad7bcfda8c6ae192"}}
