{"type":"message","id":"323cf1c0","parentId":"3c5f603e","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:58:05.657Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_JbxKYyUAzaDpYEQJ6LVZVG8m|fc_0785557c08065f410169cd4e92a6988190a4b85744faf14362","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\runtime\\s1\\supervisor_skills\\scene_director_output_normalizer.py","oldText":"def _match_scene_tokens(source_tokens: list[str], narration_tokens: list[str], cursor: int) -> int | None:\n    source_slice = source_tokens[cursor - 1 : cursor - 1 + len(narration_tokens)]\n    if len(source_slice) != len(narration_tokens):\n        return None\n\n    normalized_source = [_normalize_token(tok) for tok in source_slice]\n    normalized_narration = [_normalize_token(tok) for tok in narration_tokens]\n\n    if normalized_source != normalized_narration:\n        return None\n\n    return cursor + len(narration_tokens) - 1\n","newText":"def _match_scene_tokens(source_tokens: list[str], narration_tokens: list[str], cursor: int) -> int | None:\n    source_slice = source_tokens[cursor - 1 : cursor - 1 + len(narration_tokens)]\n    normalized_narration = [_normalize_token(tok) for tok in narration_tokens]\n\n    if len(source_slice) == len(narration_tokens):\n        normalized_source = [_normalize_token(tok) for tok in source_slice]\n        if normalized_source == normalized_narration:\n            return cursor + len(narration_tokens) - 1\n\n    best = _find_best_fuzzy_end(source_tokens, normalized_narration, cursor)\n    return best\n\n\ndef _find_best_fuzzy_end(source_tokens: list[str], narration_tokens: list[str], cursor: int) -> int | None:\n    max_window_delta = 18\n    min_ratio = 0.985\n    start_index = cursor - 1\n\n    best_ratio = 0.0\n    best_end: int | None = None\n    source_len = len(source_tokens)\n    target_len = len(narration_tokens)\n\n    for delta in range(-max_window_delta, max_window_delta + 1):\n        window_len = target_len + delta\n        if window_len <= 0:\n            continue\n        end_index = start_index + window_len\n        if end_index > source_len:\n            continue\n        candidate = [_normalize_token(tok) for tok in source_tokens[start_index:end_index]]\n        if not candidate:\n            continue\n        ratio = SequenceMatcher(None, candidate, narration_tokens).ratio()\n        if ratio > best_ratio:\n            best_ratio = ratio\n            best_end = start_index + window_len\n\n    if best_end is None or best_ratio < min_ratio:\n        return None\n\n    return best_end\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\runtime\\\\s1\\\\supervisor_skills\\\\scene_director_output_normalizer.py\",\"oldText\":\"def _match_scene_tokens(source_tokens: list[str], narration_tokens: list[str], cursor: int) -> int | None:\\n    source_slice = source_tokens[cursor - 1 : cursor - 1 + len(narration_tokens)]\\n    if len(source_slice) != len(narration_tokens):\\n        return None\\n\\n    normalized_source = [_normalize_token(tok) for tok in source_slice]\\n    normalized_narration = [_normalize_token(tok) for tok in narration_tokens]\\n\\n    if normalized_source != normalized_narration:\\n        return None\\n\\n    return cursor + len(narration_tokens) - 1\\n\",\"newText\":\"def _match_scene_tokens(source_tokens: list[str], narration_tokens: list[str], cursor: int) -> int | None:\\n    source_slice = source_tokens[cursor - 1 : cursor - 1 + len(narration_tokens)]\\n    normalized_narration = [_normalize_token(tok) for tok in narration_tokens]\\n\\n    if len(source_slice) == len(narration_tokens):\\n        normalized_source = [_normalize_token(tok) for tok in source_slice]\\n        if normalized_source == normalized_narration:\\n            return cursor + len(narration_tokens) - 1\\n\\n    best = _find_best_fuzzy_end(source_tokens, normalized_narration, cursor)\\n    return best\\n\\n\\ndef _find_best_fuzzy_end(source_tokens: list[str], narration_tokens: list[str], cursor: int) -> int | None:\\n    max_window_delta = 18\\n    min_ratio = 0.985\\n    start_index = cursor - 1\\n\\n    best_ratio = 0.0\\n    best_end: int | None = None\\n    source_len = len(source_tokens)\\n    target_len = len(narration_tokens)\\n\\n    for delta in range(-max_window_delta, max_window_delta + 1):\\n        window_len = target_len + delta\\n        if window_len <= 0:\\n            continue\\n        end_index = start_index + window_len\\n        if end_index > source_len:\\n            continue\\n        candidate = [_normalize_token(tok) for tok in source_tokens[start_index:end_index]]\\n        if not candidate:\\n            continue\\n        ratio = SequenceMatcher(None, candidate, narration_tokens).ratio()\\n        if ratio > best_ratio:\\n            best_ratio = ratio\\n            best_end = start_index + window_len\\n\\n    if best_end is None or best_ratio < min_ratio:\\n        return None\\n\\n    return best_end\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":187,"output":601,"cacheRead":207744,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":208532,"cost":{"input":0.00046750000000000003,"output":0.009015,"cacheRead":0.051935999999999996,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0614185}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775062670577,"responseId":"resp_0785557c08065f410169cd4e8f788c8190aeab7e1f787cb74d"}}
{"type":"message","id":"a7889573","parentId":"323cf1c0","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:58:06.321Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_JbxKYyUAzaDpYEQJ6LVZVG8m|fc_0785557c08065f410169cd4e92a6988190a4b85744faf14362","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\runtime\\s1\\supervisor_skills\\scene_director_output_normalizer.py."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 154 \n 155 \n 156 def _match_scene_tokens(source_tokens: list[str], narration_tokens: list[str], cursor: int) -> int | None:\n 157     source_slice = source_tokens[cursor - 1 : cursor - 1 + len(narration_tokens)]\n-158     if len(source_slice) != len(narration_tokens):\n-159         return None\n-160 \n-161     normalized_source = [_normalize_token(tok) for tok in source_slice]\n 162     normalized_narration = [_normalize_token(tok) for tok in narration_tokens]\n 163 \n-164     if normalized_source != normalized_narration:\n+160     if len(source_slice) == len(narration_tokens):\n+161         normalized_source = [_normalize_token(tok) for tok in source_slice]\n+162         if normalized_source == normalized_narration:\n+163             return cursor + len(narration_tokens) - 1\n+164 \n+165     best = _find_best_fuzzy_end(source_tokens, normalized_narration, cursor)\n+166     return best\n+167 \n+168 \n+169 def _find_best_fuzzy_end(source_tokens: list[str], narration_tokens: list[str], cursor: int) -> int | None:\n+170     max_window_delta = 18\n+171     min_ratio = 0.985\n+172     start_index = cursor - 1\n+173 \n+174     best_ratio = 0.0\n+175     best_end: int | None = None\n+176     source_len = len(source_tokens)\n+177     target_len = len(narration_tokens)\n+178 \n+179     for delta in range(-max_window_delta, max_window_delta + 1):\n+180         window_len = target_len + delta\n+181         if window_len <= 0:\n+182             continue\n+183         end_index = start_index + window_len\n+184         if end_index > source_len:\n+185             continue\n+186         candidate = [_normalize_token(tok) for tok in source_tokens[start_index:end_index]]\n+187         if not candidate:\n+188             continue\n+189         ratio = SequenceMatcher(None, candidate, narration_tokens).ratio()\n+190         if ratio > best_ratio:\n+191             best_ratio = ratio\n+192             best_end = start_index + window_len\n+193 \n+194     if best_end is None or best_ratio < min_ratio:\n 165         return None\n 166 \n-167     return cursor + len(narration_tokens) - 1\n+197     return best_end","firstChangedLine":158},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775062686205}}
{"type":"message","id":"22d0c46c","parentId":"a7889573","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:58:37.384Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_ERlcYFNc42PQ3yLv1Deu0gLy|fc_0785557c08065f410169cd4ea8e938819092d95fb9a9006b08","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\implementation\\s1\\S1_SCENE_DIRECTOR_REPAIR_FLOW.md","content":"# S1_SCENE_DIRECTOR_REPAIR_FLOW.md\n\n_Last updated: 2026-04-01_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThis document records the architectural correction made after the first real `PM -> VO -> S1` controlled tests exposed a `scene_director` failure mode.\n\nThe goal is to explain:\n- what failed\n- why prompt-only fixes were insufficient\n- what was changed in the runtime design\n- what repair direction the supervisor should support going forward\n\n---\n\n## Original failure mode\n\nDuring the first real integrated tests, the `scene_director` operator failed in two distinct ways:\n\n### 1. Global-vs-local coordinate drift\nLater batches (`sd_002` onward) returned global script coordinates instead of batch-relative coordinates.\n\nThis happened because the operator was being invoked without guaranteed fresh isolation per batch.\nThe fix for this layer was to use:\n- `openclaw agent --local`\n\n### 2. Boundary/text exactness failures\nEven after per-batch isolation improved the situation, some scene boundaries still failed because:\n- a scene could absorb the first sentence of the following scene\n- `narration_original` and declared spans could drift apart slightly\n\nThis showed that the contract was asking a semantic agent to do too much mechanical work.\n\n---\n\n## Updated design direction\n\nThe `scene_director` lane is now treated as a **hybrid lane**:\n\n### Agent responsibility\nThe agent should focus primarily on:\n- semantic scene grouping\n- scene titles\n- scene summaries\n- narrative functions\n- approximate/meaningful narration grouping\n\n### Deterministic substrate responsibility\nThe runtime should own more of the mechanical precision:\n- batch isolation\n- exact span derivation\n- exact `estimated_scene_word_count`\n- final alignment validation\n- repair/retry orchestration when a boundary fails\n\n---\n\n## Implemented runtime correction\n\nA new deterministic skill was introduced:\n- `runtime/s1/supervisor_skills/scene_director_output_normalizer.py`\n\n### Current role of the normalizer\nThe normalizer now:\n- reads the agent output\n- re-derives batch-relative spans from the batch text\n- rewrites `start_word`, `end_word`, and `estimated_scene_word_count`\n- rewrites `narration_original` from the source span when alignment is sufficiently clear\n- allows small fuzzy matching tolerance for residual boundary drift\n\nThis significantly reduced the original failure surface.\n\n---\n\n## Why prompt-only fixes were insufficient\n\nThe system already tried:\n- stronger workspace memory\n- stronger prompt wording\n- stronger examples\n- stronger supervisor invocation message\n\nThese improved clarity, but they did not eliminate the class of failure because the agent was still being asked to simultaneously do:\n- semantic grouping\n- exact text copying\n- exact word counting\n- exact local indexing\n\nThat combination is structurally fragile for an LLM.\n\n---\n\n## Repair-loop direction (important)\n\nThe preferred long-term direction is **supervisor-driven repair**, not blind full-batch regenerate.\n\n### Ideal behavior\nWhen validator/normalizer detects a localized failure such as:\n- `scene_02` absorbing the beginning of `scene_03`\n\nThe supervisor should:\n1. localize the error\n2. identify the affected scene boundary\n3. issue a repair request for only the affected scenes\n4. keep the rest of the batch fixed\n5. revalidate\n\n### Example\nInstead of saying:\n- \"regenerate `sd_002` from scratch\"\n\nthe supervisor should be able to say:\n- \"repair the boundary between `scene_02` and `scene_03`; keep `scene_01` unchanged; ensure `scene_02` ends before the first sentence of `scene_03`\"\n\n---\n\n## Current status of repair support\n\nAt the time of this document:\n- validator detection exists\n- retry planning exists\n- subset/batch targeting exists conceptually\n- fine-grained scene-boundary repair is the next architectural step to formalize fully\n\nIn other words:\n- the architecture now clearly points to scene-level or boundary-level repair\n- but the runtime is not yet fully mature in that loop\n\n---\n\n## Current practical rule\n\nFor now, the S1 runtime should prefer this sequence:\n1. isolate each batch with `--local`\n2. normalize deterministically\n3. validate\n4. if a localized boundary issue remains, treat it as a repair candidate, not proof that the whole PM/VO/S1 pipeline is broken\n\n---\n\n## Implication for future work\n\nThe `scene_director` operator should no longer be treated as the single source of truth for exact mechanical spans.\n\nThe lane should evolve toward:\n- semantic agent decisions\n- deterministic normalization\n- targeted supervisor repair when boundaries are still ambiguous\n\nThis is the cleaner and more reliable canonical direction.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\docs\\\\implementation\\\\s1\\\\S1_SCENE_DIRECTOR_REPAIR_FLOW.md\",\"content\":\"# S1_SCENE_DIRECTOR_REPAIR_FLOW.md\\n\\n_Last updated: 2026-04-01_\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Purpose\\n\\nThis document records the architectural correction made after the first real `PM -> VO -> S1` controlled tests exposed a `scene_director` failure mode.\\n\\nThe goal is to explain:\\n- what failed\\n- why prompt-only fixes were insufficient\\n- what was changed in the runtime design\\n- what repair direction the supervisor should support going forward\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Original failure mode\\n\\nDuring the first real integrated tests, the `scene_director` operator failed in two distinct ways:\\n\\n### 1. Global-vs-local coordinate drift\\nLater batches (`sd_002` onward) returned global script coordinates instead of batch-relative coordinates.\\n\\nThis happened because the operator was being invoked without guaranteed fresh isolation per batch.\\nThe fix for this layer was to use:\\n- `openclaw agent --local`\\n\\n### 2. Boundary/text exactness failures\\nEven after per-batch isolation improved the situation, some scene boundaries still failed because:\\n- a scene could absorb the first sentence of the following scene\\n- `narration_original` and declared spans could drift apart slightly\\n\\nThis showed that the contract was asking a semantic agent to do too much mechanical work.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Updated design direction\\n\\nThe `scene_director` lane is now treated as a **hybrid lane**:\\n\\n### Agent responsibility\\nThe agent should focus primarily on:\\n- semantic scene grouping\\n- scene titles\\n- scene summaries\\n- narrative functions\\n- approximate/meaningful narration grouping\\n\\n### Deterministic substrate responsibility\\nThe runtime should own more of the mechanical precision:\\n- batch isolation\\n- exact span derivation\\n- exact `estimated_scene_word_count`\\n- final alignment validation\\n- repair/retry orchestration when a boundary fails\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Implemented runtime correction\\n\\nA new deterministic skill was introduced:\\n- `runtime/s1/supervisor_skills/scene_director_output_normalizer.py`\\n\\n### Current role of the normalizer\\nThe normalizer now:\\n- reads the agent output\\n- re-derives batch-relative spans from the batch text\\n- rewrites `start_word`, `end_word`, and `estimated_scene_word_count`\\n- rewrites `narration_original` from the source span when alignment is sufficiently clear\\n- allows small fuzzy matching tolerance for residual boundary drift\\n\\nThis significantly reduced the original failure surface.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Why prompt-only fixes were insufficient\\n\\nThe system already tried:\\n- stronger workspace memory\\n- stronger prompt wording\\n- stronger examples\\n- stronger supervisor invocation message\\n\\nThese improved clarity, but they did not eliminate the class of failure because the agent was still being asked to simultaneously do:\\n- semantic grouping\\n- exact text copying\\n- exact word counting\\n- exact local indexing\\n\\nThat combination is structurally fragile for an LLM.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Repair-loop direction (important)\\n\\nThe preferred long-term direction is **supervisor-driven repair**, not blind full-batch regenerate.\\n\\n### Ideal behavior\\nWhen validator/normalizer detects a localized failure such as:\\n- `scene_02` absorbing the beginning of `scene_03`\\n\\nThe supervisor should:\\n1. localize the error\\n2. identify the affected scene boundary\\n3. issue a repair request for only the affected scenes\\n4. keep the rest of the batch fixed\\n5. revalidate\\n\\n### Example\\nInstead of saying:\\n- \\\"regenerate `sd_002` from scratch\\\"\\n\\nthe supervisor should be able to say:\\n- \\\"repair the boundary between `scene_02` and `scene_03`; keep `scene_01` unchanged; ensure `scene_02` ends before the first sentence of `scene_03`\\\"\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Current status of repair support\\n\\nAt the time of this document:\\n- validator detection exists\\n- retry planning exists\\n- subset/batch targeting exists conceptually\\n- fine-grained scene-boundary repair is the next architectural step to formalize fully\\n\\nIn other words:\\n- the architecture now clearly points to scene-level or boundary-level repair\\n- but the runtime is not yet fully mature in that loop\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Current practical rule\\n\\nFor now, the S1 runtime should prefer this sequence:\\n1. isolate each batch with `--local`\\n2. normalize deterministically\\n3. validate\\n4. if a localized boundary issue remains, treat it as a repair candidate, not proof that the whole PM/VO/S1 pipeline is broken\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Implication for future work\\n\\nThe `scene_director` operator should no longer be treated as the single source of truth for exact mechanical spans.\\n\\nThe lane should evolve toward:\\n- semantic agent decisions\\n- deterministic normalization\\n- targeted supervisor repair when boundaries are still ambiguous\\n\\nThis is the cleaner and more reliable canonical direction.\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":66241,"output":1125,"cacheRead":140800,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":208166,"cost":{"input":0.1656025,"output":0.016875,"cacheRead":0.035199999999999995,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.21767750000000002}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775062686833,"responseId":"resp_0785557c08065f410169cd4ea06f488190b268617b9b5ea774"}}
